nd":"Schotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1335–1411":"about 1335–1411","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Deceased","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1354–Male":"1354–Deceased","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1350":"1350","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","ABT. 1354":"about 1354","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1378":"1378","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","20 October 1378":"20 October 1378","about 1335":"about 1335","1417":"1417","1317":"1317","Of, Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perth, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oliphant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London) and Scottish (Fife): from Old French <i>olifard</i> or <i>olifant</i>, of uncertain meaning. It has been suggested that this might be a derivative of Old French <i>olif</i> ‘olive’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i> ‘derisive nickname for one who preferred an olive branch to more martial weapons’; it may have denoted a man twisted like an olive-tree. The variant <i>Olifant</i> may have resulted from the substitution in Old Norman French of the sequence <i>l-r</i> by <i>l-n</i>, leading to a false association with Old French <i>olifant</i> ‘elephant’. This heraldic beast appears in the Scottish family's coats of arms. Branches of the Anglo-Norman family owned lands in both England and Scotland. The surname is now chiefly Scottish.","English: possibly a topographic name from residence at an inn known as the <i>Olyphaunt</i> or ‘elephant’, though whether this gave rise to a hereditary surname is unknown."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Walter Oliphant was born about 1335, in Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Walter Oliphant, was 24 and his mother, Elizabeth de Bruce, was 19. He had at least 2 sons with Mary Erskine. He died in 1411, in Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"about 1335–1411":"umbes 1335–1411","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1313–1378":"1313–1378","1317–1364":"1317–1364","1350":"1350","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","ABT. 1354":"umbes 1354","1356":"1356","1411":"1411","1378":"1378","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","20 October 1378":"20. oktoober 1378","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1417":"1417","1317":"1317","Of, Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perth, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1335–1411":"noin 1335–1411","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","1336–1356":"1336–1356","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1348–1412":"1348–1412","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1354–Male":"1354–K